### Conditional Execution

Often you need to perform one operation or another based on a given condition. This is what it is known as conditional execution. In R, you can implement it as follows:

```{r,eval=F}
if (some_condition) {
  execute.this()
} else {
  execute.that()
}
```

The expression or object that replaces `someCondition` must evaluate to either `TRUE` or `FALSE`.

Here is an example:

```{r}
season <- 'summer'
if (season == 'summer') {
  print('hot')
} else {
  print('cold')
}
```

Conditional expressions can also be chained:

```{r,eval=F}
if (some_condition) {
  execute.this()
} else if (some_other_condition) {
  execute.that()
} else {
  execute.something.else()
}
```

or nested:

```{r,eval=F}
if (some_condition) {
  execute.this()
} else {
  if (some_other_condition) {
    execute.that()
  }
}
```

*Exercise*

Write a function that computed the square root of a number if the number is strictly positive and the square root of its absolute value if it is negative:

```{r,eval=F}
compute.square <- function(number) {
  if (some_condition) { # change the condition
    # write your code here
  } else {
    # write your code here
  }
}
```

Now check that it produces the desired result:

```{r,eval=F}
compute.square(4)
compute.square(-16)
```

*Solution*

```{r}
compute.square <- function(number) {
  if (number > 0) {
    return(sqrt(number))
  } else {
    return(sqrt(abs(number)))
  }
}
```

```{r}
compute.square(4)
compute.square(-16)
```
Notice that `if` and `else` do not work with a vector of logical values. So you'll get an error if you do

```{r, eval=F}
if (d>5) {
  d <- d + 2
}
```

For cases like this, you can use the `ifelse` function (base R)

```{r}
d_new <- ifelse(d>5,d+2,d)
d_new
```

### Loops and Repetition

Sometimes you need to repeat the same operation more than once with some variation. Here is an example:

```{r}
countdown <- function(n){
  while (n > 0) {
    print(n)
    n <- n - 1
  }
  print('Blastoff!')
}
countdown(3)
```

The `while` statement checks if a condition is `TRUE` (here `n>0`) and keeps executing the code in curly brackets when (if ever) it turns `FALSE`. Make sure that you are not setting up an infinite loop!

A second alternative when you know exactly how many iterations you need to run is the `for` statement. Here is how we wuld rewrite the `countdown` function with a `for` loop.

```{r}
countdown <- function(n){
  for (i in n:1) {
    print(i)
  }
  print('Blastoff!')
}
countdown(3)
```

## Efficient data manipulation with `data.table`

What we explored so far is part of the core R language. Indeed, we did not import any package. 

A package is a collection of functions pulled together by someone in order to perform a given set of operations. in R, packages are installed and loaded with the commands:

```{r,eval=F}
install.packages('package_name')
library(package_name)
```

Once a package is loaded, you can use its functions as if they were R core functions. If you want help with a function, you can type `?function_name` in your console to access its documentation. Also, if you just type `function_name`, with no brackets, R will print out the function's code in the console. This can be useful if the developer did not hide the function's code (which happens frequently), and if the function is not too complicated. If you just need a specific function from a certain package and don't want to load the rest of package, you can also call `package_name::function_name`. You also need to use this syntax when two loaded packages have a function with the same name and you want to make sure that the right one is used.

There are many specialized packages in R, to build visualizations, to work with geographical data, to perform text analysis, etc.. Among R packages, the [`tidyverse`](https://www.tidyverse.org) collection stands out as coherent framework to perform all the most common data science operations, from reading the data, to cleaning it, to visualizing it.

The `tidyverse` is great and has contributed to the popularity of R. But... it's not the most efficient package and struggles when handling large objects. While you can use selected `tidyverse` functions and sub-packages even with large data in certain situations (wel'll see examples from `stringr` for string manipulation and `forcats` for working with categorical variables), today I'll cover the main alternative to the `tidyverse` when efficiency is crucial (e.g. in FIONA).

Not everything you could do with the `tidyverse` is implemented in `data.table` (for example data visualization) but what you can do in `data.table` will be significantly more computationally efficient than its `tidyverse` equivalent.

### `fread` and `fwrite` Reading and Writing Data

`.csv` is by far the most common format for rectangular data. You can read `.csv` files into R using `data.table` as follows:

```{r,eval=F}
fread(path_to_file)
```

You can select which columns to read with the `select` argument, specify column types with the `colClasses` argument, and specify a non standard delimiter with the `sep` argument. We can also specify whether we want to skip a number of rows after the header with the `skip` argument and set the maximum number of rows we want to read with the `nrow` argument. These two arguments are useful to read a large dataset in chunks and process each one separately. This is a general approach to reduce RAM usage and the only solution when your machine does not have enough RAM to store the entire object into memory.

Here is a typical chunk of code to do this:

```{r,eval=F}
# Assume we know the number of rows in advance
n_rows <- 10000
chunk_size <- 1000
skips <- seq(0,n_rows,chunk_size)
my_data <- vector(mode='list',length=length(skips))

for (i in 1:length(my_data)) {
  my_data[[i]] <- fread(path_to_file,skip=skips[i],nrows=chunk_size)
}

my_data <- rbindlist(my_data) # Some people would object to this
```

`fread` is highly customizable and offers many useful options to take care of parsing problems. Unfortunately `fread` can't read stata `.dta` files, for those we have to use `read_dta` from the `haven` package (another `tidyverse` package).

Once you have transformed the data you read and are satisfied with the result, you can write it to a file as follows:

```{r,eval=F}
fwrite(transformed_data,path_to_file)
```

### `data.table` philosophy

While unintuitive at first, the core `data.table` syntax is simple and boils down to statements of the type

```{r,eval=F}
DT[i, j, by]
```

Which means "Take DT, subset/reorder rows using i, then calculate j, grouped by by." This might be familiar to you if you've ever used SQL. Sometimes, you'll just need to subset your data, and thus will only use i operations, sometimes you'll just need to add a column, or modify and existing column, and thus will only need j.

To keep things real, let us load some data we can play with. This is data from the 2010 National Health Interview Survey which I downloaded from IPUMS. It has to be read with a special syntax but then we'll save it as a csv file so we can practice both writing and reading a file.

```{r}
# Read data with IPUMS package (ipumsr)
ddi <- ipumsr::read_ipums_ddi(here('data','NHIS','nhis_00007.xml'))
data <- ipumsr::read_ipums_micro(ddi) # Example of using a function without loading the full package

# Convert to data.table
setDT(data)

# Select some variables (j operation)
data <- data[,.(NHISHID,PERWEIGHT,AGE,SEX,MARSTCUR,RACENEW,HISPETH,EDUC,BMICAT,BMICALC,DIABETICAGE,SMOKESTATUS2)]

# Write to csv file
fwrite(data,here('output','data','NHIS_data.csv'))

# Remove from memory
rm(data) # Good practice in FIONA
gc(verbose = F) # Only needed when removing large objects from memory

# Read the csv version
data <- fread(here('output','data','NHIS_data.csv'))
```

Just for fun, we can also try loading it with our memory-efficient loop. We don't know the number of rows so we'll modify our loop a bit so it automatically stops when there are no more rows.

```{r}
chunk_size <- 10000
skip_rows <- 1 # Because the header counts!
my_data <- vector(mode='list',length=10) # To keep stuff efficient we still need a guess for the max size

# Read header
header <- fread(here('outputs','data','NHIS_data.csv'), header = TRUE, nrow = 1)

# Read first chunk
my_data[[1]] <- fread(here('outputs','data','NHIS_data.csv'),nrows=chunk_size)

# Set up counter and update skip_rows
i <- 2
skip_rows <- skip_rows + chunk_size

while (nrow(my_data[[i-1]])==chunk_size) {
  my_data[[i]] <- fread(here('outputs','data','NHIS_data.csv'),skip=skip_rows,nrows=chunk_size,header=F)
  setnames( my_data[[i]], colnames(header))
  skip_rows <- skip_rows + chunk_size
  i <- i+1
}

my_data <- rbindlist(my_data) # Some people would object to this

# We don't really need this so we can remove it
rm(my_data)
gc()
```

